'''Jennifer Love Hewitt''' (born February 21, 1979)<ref name=tvg>{{cite journal| url = http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/jennifer-love-hewitt/156628| title= Jennifer Love Hewitt | magazine= [[TV Guide]]| accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref> is an American actress, singer, songwriter, producer and director. Hewitt began her career as a child actress and singer, appearing in national television commercials before joining the cast of the [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[Kids Incorporated]]'' (1989–1991) as well as performing as a backup singer before recording her debut studio album at the age of 12, ''[[Love Songs (Jennifer Love Hewitt album)|Love Songs]]'' (1992), which was released exclusively in [[Japan]]. Hewitt received her breakthrough role as Sarah Reeves Merrin on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] teen drama ''[[Party of Five]]'' (1995–1999), and rose to fame as a teen star for her role as Julie James in the horror film ''[[I Know What You Did Last Summer]]'' (1997) and its [[I Still Know What You Did Last Summer|1998 sequel]].

Hewitt released her second and third studio albums with [[Atlantic Records]], ''[[Let's Go Bang]]'' (1995) and ''[[Jennifer Love Hewitt (album)|Jennifer Love Hewitt]]'' (1996), both of which saw little commercial success. Thereafter, she starred alongside [[Sigourney Weaver]] in the romantic comedy film ''[[Heartbreakers (2001 film)|Heartbreakers]]'' (2001) and alongside [[Jackie Chan]] in the action comedy film ''[[The Tuxedo]]'' (2002). Hewitt released her fourth studio album and most recent to date with [[Jive Records]] in 2002, ''[[BareNaked]]'', which became her first album to chart in the United States, peaking at number 37 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart. Her most successful single on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] was the 1999 release "[[How Do I Deal]]", which peaked at number 59.<ref>[{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r382817|pure_url=yes}} "I Still Know What You Did Last Summer"]. ''allmusic.com''. Retrieved 2009-05-15</ref>

From 2005 to 2010, Hewitt starred as [[Melinda Gordon]] on the [[CBS]] supernatural drama ''[[Ghost Whisperer]]'', for which she received two [[Saturn Award]]s in 2007 and 2008. She later starred on the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] drama series ''[[The Client List (TV series)|The Client List]]'' from 2012 to 2013, and was previously nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award]] for the [[The Client List|pilot film]]. From 2014 to 2015, she starred as Special Agent Kate Callahan on the CBS crime drama ''[[Criminal Minds]]''. In addition to acting, she has served as a producer on some of her film and television projects. Hewitt was identified as the "number one reader choice" on the November 1999 and May 2009 covers of ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'' magazine.<ref>[http://www.maxim.com/amg/girls/girls-of-maxim/44035/maxim-covers.html]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110917220036/http://www.maxim.com/amg/girls/girls-of-maxim/44035/maxim-covers.html |date=September 17, 2011 }}</ref> ''[[TV Guide]]'' named her the sexiest woman on television in 2008.<ref name=tvguide>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/tvs-sexiest-stars/293083|title=TV's Sexiest Stars|work=TV Guide|accessdate=December 8, 2014}}</ref>

Beginning in 2018, she starred in the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] [[first responder]] drama series [[9-1-1 (TV series)|''9-1-1'']], playing 9-1-1 [[dispatcher]] Maddie Buckley.

==Early life==
Hewitt was born in [[Waco, Texas]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2005/09/21/earlyshow/leisure/celebspot/main870783.shtml|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt's 'Ghost'|last=Morales|first=Tatiana|work=The Early Show|date=February 11, 2009 |accessdate=August 14, 2011}}</ref> to Patricia Mae (née Shipp), a [[speech-language pathologist]], and Herbert Daniel Hewitt, a medical technician.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmreference.com/film/59/Jennifer-Love-Hewitt.html|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt profile at Film Reference.com|publisher=Filmreference.com|accessdate=January 20, 2011}}</ref> Hewitt grew up in [[Nolanville, Texas|Nolanville]], in [[Central Texas]],<ref name=Biography3>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Biography|url=http://www.biography.com/articles/Hewitt-Jennifer-Love-259260|work=Bio|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref> and has close kinship ties in parts of Arkansas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Biography|url=http://www.sing365.com/music/lyric.nsf/Jennifer-Love-Hewitt-Biography/C49195A3317F650B48256A960011141A|work=Sing365.com|accessdate=August 15, 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111103235722/http://www.sing365.com/music/lyric.nsf/Jennifer-Love-Hewitt-Biography/C49195A3317F650B48256A960011141A|archivedate=November 3, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> After their parents divorced, Hewitt and her older brother Todd were raised by their mother.<ref name=Biography4>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt |url=http://www.hollyscoop.com/jennifer-love-hewitt |work=Hollywood Scoop |accessdate=August 14, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809083316/http://www.hollyscoop.com/jennifer-love-hewitt |archivedate=August 9, 2011 }}</ref> Patricia Mae Hewitt died on June 12, 2012, aged 67, following a battle with cancer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/jennifer-love-hewitts-mom-patricia-dies-at-67-2012136|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt's Mom Patricia Dies at 67|date=June 13, 2012|work=usmagazine.com|accessdate=December 8, 2014}}</ref>

As a young girl, Hewitt was attracted to music, which led to her first encounters with the entertainment industry. At the age of three, she sang "[[The Greatest Love of All]]" at a livestock show.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800018784/bio|work=Yahoo! Movies|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref> The following year, at a restaurant-dance hall, she entertained an audience with her version of "Help Me Make it Through the Night".<ref name=Biography1>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Biography|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/info/jennifer_love_hewitt|work=Contact Music|accessdate=August 14, 2011}}</ref> By age five, she had [[tap dancing]] and ballet in her portfolio.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt|url=http://www.buddytv.com/info/jennifer-love-hewitt-info.aspx|work=Buddy TV|accessdate=August 14, 2011}}</ref> At nine, she became a member of the Texas Show Team (which also toured in the [[Soviet Union]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt: Biography|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/jennifer-love-hewitt/bio/156628|work=TV Guide|accessdate=August 14, 2011}}</ref>

At age ten, at the suggestion of talent scouts and after winning the title of "Texas Our Little Miss Talent Winner",<ref>{{cite news|last=Gordon|first=James|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt talks ghosts, high-heels and...|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1247431/Jennifer-Love-Hewitt-high-heels-new-star-boyfriend-Jamie-Kennedy.html|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=August 15, 2011|location=London|date=January 31, 2010}}</ref> she moved to Los Angeles with her mother to pursue a career in both acting and singing.<ref name=Biography4/> In Los Angeles, she attended [[Abraham Lincoln High School (Los Angeles)|Lincoln High School]]{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}} where her classmates included Jonathan Neville, who became a talent scout and recommended Hewitt for her role in ''[[Party of Five]]''.<ref name=Biography1/>

==Career==

===Acting===
After moving to [[Los Angeles]], Hewitt appeared in more than twenty television commercials, including some for [[Mattel]] toys.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt|url=http://sg.movies.yahoo.com/Jennifer+Love+Hewitt/biography/61640/|work=Yahoo! Movies Singapore|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref> Her first break came as a child actor on the [[Disney Channel]] variety show ''[[Kids Incorporated]]'' (1989–1991),<ref>{{cite web|last=Valiente|first=Maria|title=Choreographer's Corner: Yay for Dee Caspary!|url=http://www.wetpaint.com/so-you-think-you-can-dance/articles/choreographers-corner-yay-for-dee-caspary|work=Wet Paint.com|accessdate=August 14, 2011}}</ref> where she was credited as "Love Hewitt." She later appeared in the live action [[VHS|video]] short ''Dance! Workout with Barbie'' (1992), released by Buena Vista.<ref>{{cite news|last=Herman|first=Valli|title=Barbie Exercises|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FkFWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YeoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3521,3015495&dq=dance+workout+with+barbie|accessdate=August 14, 2011|newspaper=Gainesville Sun|date=March 11, 1992}}</ref>

She played [[Pierce Brosnan]]'s daughter in a pilot for [[NBC]] called ''Running Wilde'' (1993), which featured Brosnan as a reporter for ''Auto World'' magazine, whose stories cover his own wild auto adventures. However, the series was not picked up and the pilot never aired.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pierce's Brosnan's proposed ''Running Wilde''|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NpgsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VfwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4013,2155941&dq=running+wilde+pierce|accessdate=August 15, 2011|newspaper=Lakeland Ledger|date=November 14, 1992}}</ref> Hewitt later had roles in several short-lived television series, such as Fox's ''[[Shaky Ground]]'' (1992–1993),<ref>{{cite news|title=Shaky ground indeed|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Li5iAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OncNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4491,4685858&dq=shaky+ground+fox+hewitt|accessdate=August 14, 2011|newspaper=Observer-Reporter|date=December 12, 1992}}</ref> [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[The Byrds of Paradise]]'' (1994),<ref>{{cite news|last=Biddle|first=Frederic M.|title=ABC's fledgling 'Byrds' wings it on the weird side|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/61927337.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Mar+03%2C+1994&author=Frederic+M.+Biddle%2C+Globe+Staff&pub=Boston+Globe+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=ABC's+fledgling+'Byrds'+wings+it+on+the+weird+side&pqatl=google|work=Boston Globe |accessdate=August 14, 2011|date=March 3, 1994}}</ref> and ''[[McKenna (TV series)|McKenna]]'' (1994–95),<ref>{{cite news|title=Fall TV Preview Thursday night all shook up|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/projo/access/575882561.html?dids=575882561:575882561&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep+01%2C+1994&author=John+Martin&pub=The+Providence+Journal&desc=Fall+TV+Preview+Thursday+night+all+shook+up&pqatl=google|work=Projo.com|accessdate=August 14, 2011|first=John|last=Martin|date=September 1, 1994}}</ref> and finally became a young star after landing the role of Sarah Reeves Merrin on the popular [[Fox Television|Fox]] show ''[[Party of Five]]'' (1995–99).<ref>{{cite news|last=Fretts|first=Bruce|title=Party of Five|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,299985,00.html|publisher=EW.com|date=December 15, 1995}}</ref> She assumed the role of Sarah after joining that show during its second season and continued it on the short-lived ''Party of Five'' spin-off, ''[[Time of Your Life (U.S. TV series)|Time of Your Life]]'' (1999), which she also co-produced.<ref>{{cite news|last=Huff|first=Richard|title=Trouble Denied on New Hewitt Show|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/1999-07-23/entertainment/18109986_1_producer-title-time-slot-amy-lippman|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=August 14, 2011|location=New York|date=July 23, 1999}}</ref> The show was cancelled after half a season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Huff|first=Richard|title=2 Fox Series Face Reality 'Survivor' Delays Debut; 'time' Runs Out For 'life'|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2000-06-27/entertainment/18126508_1_fox-survivor-stacey-lynn-koerner|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=August 14, 2011|location=New York|date=June 27, 2000}}</ref>

Hewitt's first feature film role was in the [[independent film]] ''[[Munchie]]'' (1992).<ref>{{cite news|title=At home with Hewitt|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cUAhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ansFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1996,884502&dq=jennifer+love+hewitt+munchie|accessdate=September 30, 2011|newspaper=''New Straits Times''|date=October 12, 2002}}</ref> A year later, she achieved her first starring film role in ''[[Little Miss Millions]]'' (1993). She appeared as a choir member in ''[[Sister Act 2: Back in the Habit]]'' (1993).<ref>{{cite news|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt: The Girl Next Door|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Ux4iAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EwsEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6621,2172554&dq=jennifer+love+hewitt+sister+act+2|accessdate=August 14, 2011|newspaper=Manila Standard|date=February 16, 1998}}</ref> Hewitt became a film star after a lead role in the horror film ''[[I Know What You Did Last Summer]]'' (1997),<ref>{{cite news|title=Film business has some drawbacks|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=XWZAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BlcMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4603,3885976&dq=i+know+what+you+did+last+summer+hewitt|accessdate=August 15, 2011|newspaper=The Robesonian|date=August 14, 1997}}</ref> which enjoyed great box office success (US$125,000,000).<ref>{{cite web|title=Box Office for I Know What...|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0119345/business|work=The Internet Movie Database|accessdate=August 14, 2011}}</ref> Hewitt and her co-stars gained popular exposure from the film. She appeared in the sequel ''[[I Still Know What You Did Last Summer]]'' (1998), which, though not as successful as the first film, took in more money on its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite news|title=Top 10 Movies|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/1998-11-16/entertainment/18078387_1_million-debut-waterboy-second-consecutive-weekend|work=Daily News|accessdate=August 14, 2011|location=New York|date=November 16, 1998}}</ref> She starred in the high-school comedy ''[[Can't Hardly Wait]]'' (1998).<ref>{{cite news|last=Portman|first=Jamie|title=Can't Hardly Wait|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/498624011.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+11%2C+1998&author=Jamie+Portman&pub=Waterloo+Region+Record&desc=Can't+Hardly+Wait+She's+a+rising+star+of+movies+and+television%2C+but+Jennifer+Love+Hewitt+sounds+like+a+typical+teenager+.+.+.+the+right+sound+for+a+high+school+graduation+film&pqatl=google|work=The Star.com|accessdate=August 14, 2011|date=June 11, 1998}}</ref>

Hewitt starred in ''[[The Audrey Hepburn Story]]'' (2000).<ref>{{cite news|last=Greene|first=Josh|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Stars in Audrey Hepburn ABC biopic|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=U9hgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dXINAAAAIBAJ&pg=6477,4759285&dq=jennifer+love+hewitt+audrey+hepburn|accessdate=August 14, 2011|newspaper=The Rochester Sentinel|date=March 25, 2000}}</ref> That same year, she was the "most popular actress on television" for her [[Q Score|Q-rating]] (a measurement of a celebrity's popularity) of 37.<ref>{{cite web|title=Actress Jennifer Love Hewitt Joins Nokia To Connect with a Fresh Crowd|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Actress+Jennifer+Love+Hewitt+Joins+Nokia+To+Connect+With+A+Fresh...-a062982167|work=Business Wire|accessdate=August 14, 2011}}</ref> Noting her "Q-rating," [[Nokia]] chose her to become its spokesperson.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nokia, Jennifer Love Hewitt and Big Brothers Big Sisters of America|url=http://www.bowwowconsulting.com/pages/JLH-PSA.pdf|work=Bow-Wow Consulting|accessdate=August 14, 2011}}</ref>

She starred alongside [[Sigourney Weaver]] in the romantic comedy ''[[Heartbreakers (2001 film)|Heartbreakers]]'' (2001)<ref>{{cite news|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|title=Heartbreakers (2001)|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,280511,00.html|work=EW.com|accessdate=August 14, 2011|date=March 30, 2001}}</ref> and did voiceover work in the animated film ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame II]]'' (2002) as Madellaine, the main protagonist's love interest.<ref>{{cite web|title=Toon Talk: Hunchback of Notre Dame 2|url=http://www.laughingplace.com/News-PID114360-114361.asp|work=Laughing Place|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref> Hewitt wrote and performed "I'm Gonna Love You" for the film; the song won "Best Original Song" at the DVD Premiere Awards.<ref>{{cite news|author= Brian M. Raftery |date=February 7, 2003 |title=Fete Accomplished|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,417990,00.html |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=October 10, 2011}}</ref> She starred alongside [[Jackie Chan]] in ''[[The Tuxedo]]'' (2002),<ref>{{cite web|title=The Tuxedo |url=http://www.boxofficeprophets.com/tickermaster/listing.cfm?TMID=574:The_Tuxedo |work=Box Office Prophets |accessdate=August 14, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521064339/http://www.boxofficeprophets.com/tickermaster/listing.cfm?TMID=574%3AThe_Tuxedo |archivedate=May 21, 2013 }}</ref> which received negative reviews from critics but was a box office success.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Tuxedo (2002)|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=tuxedo.htm|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref> Hewitt appeared in ''[[If Only (film)|If Only]]'' (2004) and co-wrote and performed "Love Will Show You Everything" and "Take My Heart Back" for the film's soundtrack. She starred in ''[[Garfield: The Movie|Garfield]]'' (2004),<ref>{{cite web|title=Meyer and Love Hewitt join "Garfield"|url=http://www.moviehole.net/20031585-meyer-and-love-hewitt-join-garfield|work=Movie Hole|accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref> which became her highest-grossing film to date (US$200,804,534).<ref>{{cite web|title=Garfield: The Movie|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=garfield.htm|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref> She reprised her role for the sequel, ''[[Garfield: A Tail of Two Kitties]]'' (2006),<ref>{{cite web|last=Booth|first=Philip|title='Garfield' more tabby than tiger|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2006/06/15/Weekend/_Garfield__more_tabby.shtml|work=St. Petersburg Times Online|accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref> which, though it did not perform as well as its predecessor, achieved a strong box office gross.<ref>{{cite web|title=Garfield: A Tail of Two Kitties|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=garfield2.htm|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref>

Hewitt starred in the television series ''[[Ghost Whisperer]]'' (2005–2010),<ref>{{cite web|last=Cericola|first=Rachel|title=CBS Picks Up ''Ghost Whisperer''|url=http://www.tvfodder.com/archives/2005/10/cbs_picks_up_gh.shtml|work=TV Fodder|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref> which ran on [[CBS]] for five seasons before being canceled by the network in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|title=Breaking: CBS cancels 'Ghost Whisperer' and 'Old Christine'|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/05/18/cbs-cancels-ghost-whisperer-and-old-christine/|work=Inside TV|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref> She reunited with her ''I Know What You Did Last Summer'' co-star, [[Freddie Prinze Jr.]], in ''[[Delgo (film)|Delgo]]''; but when released in 2008, the film was a massive [[box office bomb]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Venutolo|first=Anthony|title='Delgo' is a no-go|url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2008/12/delgo_is_a_nogo.html|work=Nj.com|accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref> taking in only US$694,782 domestically.<ref>{{cite web|title=Delgo (2008)|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=delgo.htm|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref>

Hewitt's next feature film was the independent drama ''[[Café (film)|Café]]'' (2010) with her then-boyfriend [[Jamie Kennedy]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Billington|first=Alex|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Joins The Ensemble Drama ''Cafe''|url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2009/jennifer-love-hewitt-joins-the-indie-ensemble-drama-cafe/|work=First Showing|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref> She starred in the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] film ''[[The Client List]]'' (2010),<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt's "The Client List"|url=http://celebrity-gossip.net/jennifer-love-hewitt/jennifer-love-hewitts-client-list-385899|work=Celebrity Gossip|accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref> for which she received a [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] nomination.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bauder|first=David|title='Glee' leads TV nominations in Golden Globes|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2010/12/14/glee_leads_tv_nominations_in_golden_globes/|work=Boston Globe |accessdate=September 30, 2011|date=December 14, 2010}}</ref> The next year, Hewitt starred in the [[Hallmark Hall of Fame]] film ''[[The Lost Valentine]]'' (2011).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zap2it.com/news/zap-lost-valentine-story,0,2050199.story|title='Lost': Story tellers - Zap2it - News & Features|author=Ryan McGee|date=May 19, 2008|work=Zap2it|accessdate=December 8, 2014}}</ref>

In 2011, Hewitt was announced to direct the film ''Wait Till Helen Comes'' (based on [[Wait Till Helen Comes: A Ghost Story|the novel]] by [[Mary Downing Hahn]]).<ref>{{cite news|last=Alexander|first=Bryan|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt to Make Movie Directorial Debut in Ghost Story|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jennifer-love-hewitt-movie-directorial-72280|work=Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref> She had previously directed three episodes of ''Ghost Whisperer'', and this would be her feature film directorial debut.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118030302|title=Advertisement|work=Variety|accessdate=December 8, 2014}}</ref> Production on the film was slated to begin in the summer of 2011, but no further announcements about the film have been made {{as of|2015|January|lc=y}}. She also starred alongside [[Ivan Sergei]] and [[Joel David Moore]] in the [[independent film|independent]] [[comedy film|comedy]] ''[[Jewtopia (film)|Jewtopia]]'' (2012).<ref>{{cite web|last=Propst|first=Andy|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt, Joel David Moore, Ivan Sergei Set for Jewtopia Movie|url=http://www.theatermania.com/los-angeles/news/08-2011/jennifer-love-hewitt-joel-david-moore-ivan-sergei_38928.html|work=Theater Mania|accessdate=September 24, 2011}}</ref>

Hewitt was a guest star on [[TV Land]]'s ''[[Hot in Cleveland]]'' in 2011 and 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sullivan|first=Molly|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt plays Joe Jonas' fiancee on 'Hot in Cleveland'|url=http://www.hollywoodnews.com/2012/01/25/jennifer-love-hewitt-plays-joe-jonas-fiancee-on-hot-in-cleveland/|work=Hollywood News.com|accessdate=January 28, 2012}}</ref> She starred in the television series ''[[The Client List (TV series)|The Client List]]'' (2012–13) until its cancellation in late 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|title=Lifetime Orders Jennifer Love Hewitt's 'The Client List' to Series|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/lifetime-orders-jennifer-love-hewitts-221494|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=September 24, 2011|date=August 10, 2011}}</ref>

In July 2014, CBS announced that Hewitt had joined the cast of ''[[Criminal Minds (TV series)|Criminal Minds]]'' as Agent Kate Callahan in the series' 10th season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.com/shows/criminal_minds/insider_blog/1002704/ |title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Joins the Team: Casting News Update! - Criminal Minds - CBS.com |publisher=CBS Interactive |work=CBS |accessdate=December 8, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016180638/http://www.cbs.com/shows/criminal_minds/insider_blog/1002704/ |archivedate=October 16, 2014 }}</ref> However, Hewitt became pregnant with her second child during the production of season 10 of ''Criminal Minds'', and left the cast of the show at the end of the season, with the possibility of further appearances left open.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Natalie|last=Abrams |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/06/jennifer-love-hewitt-exits-criminal-minds-season11 |title=Jennifer Love Hewitt not returning for Criminal Minds season 11 -- EXCLUSIVE |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=May 6, 2015 |accessdate=May 7, 2015}}</ref>

===Music===
Hewitt was one of the back-up singers in [[Martika]]'s number-one single, "[[Toy Soldiers (song)|Toy Soldiers]]" (1989).
At the age of 12, [[Meldac]] funded the recording of Hewitt's debut studio album, ''[[Love Songs (Jennifer Love Hewitt album)|Love Songs]]'' (1992).<ref name=Album1>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/jennifer-love-hewitt/biography|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> The album was released exclusively in Japan, where Hewitt became a pop star.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|title=Hewitt Writing Country Songs|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/story/hewitt-writing-country-songs_1103790|work=Contact Music|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> Her explanation for her success in Japan is that the Japanese "love perky music. The poppier the music, the better."<ref>[http://usaweekend.com/98_issues/981122/981122talk.html] {{dead link|date=September 2011}}</ref>

After she joined the cast of ''Party of Five'', she signed to [[Atlantic Records]], who rushed her second studio album, ''[[Let's Go Bang]]'' (1995), out in October.<ref name=Album1/> The album and its three singles failed to chart.<ref name=Album1/> Juggling her music career with her acting career, she recorded and released her self-titled follow-up album, ''[[Jennifer Love Hewitt (album)|Jennifer Love Hewitt]]'' (1996).<ref>{{cite web|title=''Jennifer Love Hewitt'' by Jennifer Love Hewitt |url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/jennifer-love-hewitt/albums/jennifer-love-hewitt--7394 |work=Yahoo! Music |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726094600/http://new.music.yahoo.com/jennifer-love-hewitt/albums/jennifer-love-hewitt--7394 |archivedate=July 26, 2010 }}</ref> The album, along with its four singles, failed to chart and Atlantic dropped Hewitt, who did not return to the music scene for three years.<ref name=Album1/>

She recorded the single "[[How Do I Deal]]" (1999) for the ''[[I Still Know What You Did Last Summer]]'' soundtrack. The song became Hewitt's first charting single, climbing to No. 59 on the [[Hot 100]] and No. 36 on the [[Top 40 Mainstream]].<ref name=Album2>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt, Joel David Moore to Lead JEWTOPIA Film|url=http://broadwayworld.com/article/Jennifer-Love-Hewitt-Joel-David-Moore-to-Lead-JEWTOPIA-Film-20110808|work=Broadway World|accessdate=August 14, 2011}}</ref> It reached No. 8 in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|title=How Do I Deal (Song)|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Jennifer+Love+Hewitt&titel=How+Do+I+Deal&cat=s|work=Australian Charts.com|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> Hewitt also recorded a cover of the [[Gloria Gaynor]] song "[[I Will Survive]]", which features briefly in the film.<ref>{{cite news|title='I Know' therefore I scream|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB042E9EE88504E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D|accessdate=August 16, 2011|newspaper=Star Telegram|date=November 13, 1998}}</ref>

She appeared in the [[LFO (group)|LFO]] video for "[[Girl on TV]]" (1999),<ref>{{cite news|last=Marquard|first=Bryan|title=Rich Cronin dies at 36; singer of band LFO scored hit with 'Summer Girls'|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2010/09/rich_cronin_who.html|work=Boston Globe |accessdate=August 14, 2011|date=September 9, 2010}}</ref> a song which band member [[Rich Cronin]] band wrote for her while the two were dating.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fink|first=Mitchell|title=Hewitt's secret love: 'I can't believe she's mine'|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/gossip/2001/03/02/2001-03-02__hewitt_s_secret_love___i_ca.html|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=October 1, 2011|location=New York|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110413031813/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/gossip/2001/03/02/2001-03-02__hewitt_s_secret_love___i_ca.html |archivedate=2011-04-13}}</ref> She also appeared in the music video for the [[Enrique Iglesias]] song, "[[Hero (Enrique Iglesias song)|Hero]]" (2001), as the singer's love interest.<ref>{{cite news|last=Manan|first=Dazman|title=At Home with Hewitt|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cUAhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ansFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1996,884502&dq=jennifer+love+hewitt+enrique|accessdate=August 14, 2011|newspaper=Life & Times|date=October 12, 2002}}</ref>

In 2002, Hewitt signed to [[Jive Records]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Makes Rock Record|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1457731/jennifer-love-hewitt-rocks-out-on-new-lp.jhtml?_requestid=5618|work=VH1|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> and recorded her [[BareNaked|fourth studio album]] with singer, songwriter, and producer [[Meredith Brooks]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt's Jive Records Debut|url=http://www.mi2n.com/press.php3?press_nb=37951|work=Mi2N.com|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> The first single, "[[BareNaked (song)|BareNaked]]" (2002), became her biggest radio hit to date when it peaked at No. 24 on the [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]] chart, No. 31 on the [[Adult Top 40]] and No. 25 on the [[Top 40 Mainstream]]. It climbed to No. 6 in Australia, remaining there for two weeks,<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt – BareNaked (song)|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Jennifer+Love+Hewitt&titel=Bare+Naked&cat=s|work=Australian Charts|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> and reached No. 33 in [[Dutch Top 40|the Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt – BareNaked|url=http://acharts.us/song/6873|work=Acharts.us|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> The song later featured in two episodes of ''Ghost Whisperer'': "The Vanishing" (Season 1, episode 20)<ref>{{cite web|title=The Vanishing Trivia and Questions|url=http://www.tv.com/ghost-whisperer/the-vanishing/episode/653850/trivia.html|work=TV.com|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> and "The Collector" (Season 2, episode 20).<ref>{{cite web|title=The Collector Trivia and Questions|url=http://www.tv.com/ghost-whisperer/the-collector/episode/981209/trivia.html|work=TV.com|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> The moderate success of the single propelled the album to peak at No. 37 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref>{{cite web|title=BareNaked – Jennifer Love Hewitt|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=jennifer love hewitt|chart=all}}|work=Billboard |accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> and No. 31 in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|title=BareNaked (album)|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Jennifer+Love+Hewitt&titel=Bare+Naked&cat=a|work=Australian Charts.com|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> However, it only remained on the chart for three weeks. The second single, "[[Can I Go Now]]" (2003), failed to chart in the US, while managing to peak at No. 8 in the Netherlands<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt – Can I Go Now?|url=http://acharts.us/song/2311|work=Acharts.us|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> and No. 12 in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Can I Go Now? (song)|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Jennifer+Love+Hewitt&titel=Can+I+Go+Now%3F&cat=s|work=Australian Charts.com|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref>

Since 2004, Hewitt has remained inactive in the music industry, but she released the compilation albums ''[[Cool with You: The Platinum Collection]]'' (2006) in Asia<ref>{{cite web|title=Cool With You: Platinum Collection|url=https://www.amazon.com/Cool-You-Platinum-Collection-Chi/dp/B000FBHC6O#Product-Details|work=Amazon.com|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> and ''Hey Everybody'' (2007) in Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hey Everybody|url=http://www.enotes.com/topic/Hey_Everybody|work=eNotes|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref> In 2009, reports surfaced that Hewitt was planning on making a [[country music|country]] album and was in the process of writing material for it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Report: Jennifer Love Hewitt to Make a Country Music Album|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2009/05/20/report-jennifer-love-hewitt-make-country-music-album/|work=FOX News|accessdate=August 16, 2011|date=May 20, 2009}}</ref> [[Jamie Kennedy]], Hewitt's boyfriend at the time, said: "I really want to make her a new demo for her music, because I think she should do singing again. She's so good."<ref name=autogenerated1 /> However, nothing has of yet come of the reports. Hewitt has remained mostly absent from the music industry, but in 2013, she recorded a cover of "[[I'm a Woman (song)|I'm a Woman]]" to promote the second season of ''The Client List'' and shot a music video for the song, which reached the top ten in the iTunes Music Video chart.<ref>{{cite web|last=Feliciano|first=Kristina|title=Matthew Rolston and Jennifer Love Hewitt join forces for "I'm a Woman," the sexy new promotional music video for Lifetime's hit series "The Client List"|url=http://stocklandmartelblog.com/2013/02/11/matthew-rolston-and-jennifer-love-hewitt-music-video/|publisher=Stockland Martel|accessdate=February 12, 2013}}</ref>

===Writing===
In November 2009, Hewitt made a foray into comic books. Writer [[Scott Lobdell]] scripted the five-issue anthology, ''[[Jennifer Love Hewitt's Music Box]]'' (2009–2010), based on Hewitt's ideas.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Jennifer Love Hewitt's Music Box @ IDW''|url=http://www.comicbox.com/index.php/news-english/jennifer-love-hewitts-music-box-idw/|accessdate=August 14, 2011|date=July 26, 2011}}</ref> The series was published by [[IDW Publishing]], and was collected in a [[Trade paperback (comics)|trade paperback]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt's Music Box |url=http://www.idwpublishing.com/catalog/series/838 |work=IDW Publishing |accessdate=August 14, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827221736/http://www.idwpublishing.com/catalog/series/838 |archivedate=August 27, 2011 }}</ref>

She wrote a book titled ''[[The Day I Shot Cupid]]'' (2010), in which she speaks of her experiences with love and dating.<ref>{{cite news|last=Memmott|first=Carol|title=Confessions of 'Love-aholic' writer Jennifer Love Hewitt|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/books/news/2010-03-23-hewitt23_ST_N.htm|work=USA Today|accessdate=August 16, 2011|date=March 23, 2010}}</ref> During a January 2010 interview on  ''[[Lopez Tonight]]'', Hewitt said that there was a chapter in the book about "[[vajazzle|vajazzling]]" her "vajayjay" (decorating her [[vulva]] with [[Swarovski]] crystals);<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2010/01/jennifer-love-hewitt-explains-her-precious-lady-jewels/1 | work=USA Today | title=Jennifer Love Hewitt explains her 'precious lady' jewels | date=January 13, 2010 | accessdate=May 6, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/01/13/jennifer-love-hewitt-beda_n_421751.html |title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Bedazzled Her Privates (VIDEO) |work=Huffington Post  |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |first=Katy |last=Hall |date=January 13, 2010}}</ref> Hewitt is said to have contributed to the popularization of this trend.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celebrities spark 'vajazzling' trend|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/3991133|work=Stuff|accessdate=September 26, 2011}}</ref> The book became a [[The New York Times Bestseller List|''New York Times ''Bestseller]] the week of its release.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hardcover Advice & Misc.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2010-04-11/hardcover-advice/list.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=August 16, 2011|first=Gregory|last=Cowles}}</ref> She announced via her Twitter page in June 2011 that she was penning a follow-up.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hewitt|first=Jennifer Love|title=TheReal_Jlh|url=https://twitter.com/TheReal_Jlh/status/85883707344429056|work=Twitter|accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref>

==Personal life==
In 2002, a [[conspiracy theorist]] and former [[social worker]], [[Diana Napolis]], was arrested for [[stalking]] and uttering death threats against Hewitt and [[Steven Spielberg]] after "verbally confronting" the actress at the [[44th Grammy Awards|2002 Grammy Awards]] and attempting to pose as one of Hewitt's friends to enter the premiere of ''[[The Tuxedo]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spielberg wins order banning cult stalker|work=The Australian|date=October 23, 2002|page=12}}</ref>

Napolis admitted to being involved in a shoving match with Hewitt's mother while confronting the actress.<ref name=Mirror>{{cite news|title=Spielberg Stalker in Mind-Bug Game|publisher=[[Sunday Mirror]]|last=MacKenzie|first=D|page=16|date=October 20, 2002}}</ref> Napolis accused Hewitt, along with director Spielberg, of controlling her thoughts through "cybertronic" technology and being part of a [[Satanic ritual abuse|Satanic conspiracy]] against her.<ref name=Sauer2002>{{cite news|publisher=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]] |last=Sauer |first=M |date=December 31, 2002 |accessdate=October 30, 2008 |title=Stalking suspect to undergo more psychological tests |url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/metro/20021231-9999_1m31stalker.html |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906133859/http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/metro/20021231-9999_1m31stalker.html |archivedate=September 6, 2008 |df= }}</ref> Napolis was charged with six [[Felony|felonies]] related to the incidents.<ref>{{cite news|title=J.Love Stalker Case Ends in Guilty Plea|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,626932,00.html|accessdate=October 2, 2015|publisher=people.com|date=September 30, 2003}}</ref><ref name=DeYoung>{{cite book|author=De Young, Mary|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson, N.C.|year=2004|isbn=0-7864-1830-3|accessdate=October 30, 2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_e8ZkJBtz0EC&pg=PA234|title=The day care ritual abuse moral panic}}</ref> After a year of [[involuntary commitment]], Napolis pleaded guilty and was released on bail with a condition that she was barred from any contact with both Spielberg and Hewitt.<ref>{{cite news|title=Woman Who Stalked Actress Sentenced to Probation, Mental Health Counseling|publisher=City News Service|date=November 5, 2003}}</ref>

In late 2005, Hewitt began dating Scottish actor [[Ross McCall]] after he made an appearance on her show ''[[Ghost Whisperer]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Engaged|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Xn9PAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rwQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5773,4352915&dq=jennifer+love+hewitt+ross+mccall+us+weekly|accessdate=August 16, 2011|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=November 30, 2007}}</ref> They became engaged in November 2007, while vacationing in Hawaii.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telerate.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSN2865348420071129 |title=Jennifer Love Hewitt engaged to be married |publisher=Telerate.com |date=February 9, 2009 |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216143358/http://www.telerate.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSN2865348420071129 |archivedate=December 16, 2008 }}</ref> ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine reported that Hewitt called off their engagement in late 2008.<ref>Alexis Chiu (January 5, 2009). [http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20250077,00.html "Jennifer Love Hewitt and Fiance Split"], People.com; accessed September 3, 2015.</ref>

In March 2012, Hewitt began dating her ''[[The Client List]]'' co-star [[Brian Hallisay]].<ref name="us2013">{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Pregnant, Expecting a Baby With Brian Hallisay|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-moms/news/jennifer-love-hewitt-pregnant-expecting-a-baby-with-brian-hallisay-201346|publisher=Us Magazine|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref> In June 2013, Hewitt announced that she and Hallisay were engaged<ref name="people2013">{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Is Engaged|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20706246,00.html|publisher=People|accessdate=June 9, 2013|date=June 5, 2013|first=Andrea|last=Billups}}</ref> and expecting their first child.<ref name="us2013"/> A November 26, 2013 ''[[Us Weekly]]'' article reported that they had recently married, and their daughter was born that month.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Gives Birth to Baby Girl Autumn James, Secretly Married Brian Hallisay|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-moms/news/jennifer-love-hewitt-gives-birth-to-baby-girl-autumn-james-secretly-married-brian-hallisay-20132611|publisher=Us Weekly|accessdate=November 26, 2013|date=November 26, 2013|first=Nicole|last=Eggenberger}}</ref><ref name="people20132">{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Welcomes Daughter Autumn James|url=http://celebritybabies.people.com/2013/11/26/jennifer-love-hewitt-welcomes-daughter-autumn-james|publisher=People|accessdate=November 26, 2013|date=November 26, 2013}}</ref>
In January 2015, the couple announced they were expecting their second child.<ref name="people2015">{{cite web|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Expecting Second Child|url=http://celebritybabies.people.com/2015/01/07/jennifer-love-hewitt-pregnant-brian-hallisay-expecting-second-child/|publisher=People|accessdate=January 7, 2015|date = January 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2901417/Jennifer-Love-Hewitt-Brian-Hallisay-confirm-expecting-second-child.html|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt pregnant with her and Brian Hallisay's second child|date=January 8, 2015|work=Mail Online}}</ref> In June 2015, Hewitt gave birth to a boy.<ref name=dailymail>{{cite web|last1=Kirby|first1=Iona|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-3138524/Jennifer-Love-Hewitt-welcomes-second-child-husband-Brian-Hallisay-gives-unusual-name.html|publisher=[[The Daily Mail]]|title=It's a boy! Jennifer Love Hewitt welcomes her second child with husband Brian Hallisay... and gives him an unusual name|accessdate=June 25, 2015|date=June 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebritybabies.people.com/2015/06/24/jennifer-love-hewitt-welcomes-son-atticus-james/|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Welcomes Son Atticus James – Moms & Babies – Celebrity Babies and Kids - Moms & Babies - People.com|work=People}}</ref>

Hewitt is a supporter of the Scottish football team [[Glasgow Celtic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=B0ofujH03Og|title=Jennifer Love Hewitt Celtic Supporter}}</ref>

