{{Other uses}} {{see also|Vedette (cabaret)|Chorus line}} {{Expand German|Showgirl|date=September 2017}} [[File:Show-girl (La Cocotte) at Scala Theatre, The Hague, by Isaac Israels.jpg|thumb|Show-girl (La Cocotte) at Scala Theatre, [[The Hague]]; by [[Isaac Israëls]]]] A '''showgirl''' is a female dancer or performer in a stage entertainment show intended to showcase the performer's physical attributes, typically by way of revealing clothing or even [[toplessness]] or nudity. Showgirls are often associated with [[Latin music]] and dance, particularly [[samba]]. {{Citation needed|date=November 2015}}
The term ''show girl'' is sometimes applied to a [[promotional model]] employed in trade fairs and car shows.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ban on car show girls at Beijing Auto Show gives male attendants center stage|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/04/26/ban-on-car-show-girls-at-beijing-auto-show-gives-male-attendants-center-stage.html|date=26 April 2016|work=CNBC|author=Haze Fan}}</ref>
== History== {{Expand section|date=April 2014}} Showgirls date back to the late 1800s in Parisian [[music hall]]s and [[cabaret]]s such as the [[Moulin Rouge]], [[Le Lido]], and the [[Folies Bergère]].<ref name=oksg>{{cite web |url=http://oklahomashowgirls.com/about/history-of-showgirls/ |title=History of Showgirls |author= |date= |work=Oklahoma Showgirls |publisher= |accessdate=14 September 2017}}</ref> The trafficking of showgirls for the purposes of prostitution was the subject of a salacious novel by the nineteenth-century French author [[Ludovic Halévy]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Georges Bizet: Carmen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UNGaPmlHFzgC|first= Susan|last=McClary|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1992|isbn=9780521398978|series=Cambridge Opera Handbooks|page=38}}</ref>
==The Las Vegas showgirl== <!-- Redirect anchor from Las Vegas showgirl --> [[Image:JubileeDancersByPhilKonstantin.jpg|thumb|Jubilee! showgirls]] The first casino on the [[Las Vegas Strip]] to employ dancing girls as a diversion between acts was the [[El Rancho Vegas]] in 1941.<ref>{{cite book| title=Showgirls of Las Vegas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EDUoFbrnPxEC|last=Gioia-Acres|first=Lisa|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2013|isbn=9780738596532|page=8}}</ref> Showgirls were presented in Las Vegas in 1952 as the opening and closing act for [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] [[headliner (performances)|headliner]]s, sometimes dancing around the headliner. They were introduced at the [[Sands Casino]] for a show with [[Danny Thomas]]. In 1957 [[Minsky's Follies]] took the stage at the [[Desert Inn]] giving birth to the topless showgirl in Vegas. This was followed by a long-running ''The Lido de Paris'' at the [[Stardust Casino]] that ran for 31 years.<ref name=oksg/><ref name=pbsae>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/lasvegas/peopleevents/p_entertainers.html |title=Las Vegas: An Unconventional History |author= |date= |work=[[PBS]] |publisher= |accessdate=April 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Las Vegas Showgirls: Show and (a lot to) tell |author=Mary Manning |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2008/may/15/showgirls-may-be-fewer-numbers-will-always-be-icon/ |newspaper=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |date=May 15, 2008 |accessdate=April 22, 2012}}</ref>
==Revues with showgirls== [[Image:Psfollies.jpg|thumb|The showgirls of The Fabulous Palm Springs Follies]] {{div col|colwidth=25em}} * ''[[Calypso Cabaret]]'' (Bangkok, Thailand) * ''[[Folies Bergère]]'' (Paris) * ''[[Folies du Lac]]'' (Paris) * ''[[Jubilee!|Jubilee! Bally's]]'' (Las Vegas) * ''[[La Nouvelle Eve]]'' (Paris) * ''[[Le Lido]]'' (Paris) * ''[[Moulin Rouge]]'' (Paris) * ''[[Paradis Latin]]'' (Paris) * ''[[Roderick Palazuelos 'Platinum Stars']]'' (México) * ''Splash'' ([[Riviera (hotel and casino)|Riviera]], Las Vegas) ([[Frank Marino (female impersonator)|Frank Marino]] Show - La Cage) * ''[[The Fabulous Palm Springs Follies]]'' ([[Palm Springs, California|Palm Springs]], [[California]]; unique in that the chorus line is of showgirls in their 50s, 60s and 70s) * ''[[The Francis Show]] (Transvestite Show)'' (México) * ''[[Tihany Spectacular Circus]]'' (Brazil-México) * ''[[Tropicana Club]]'' ([[Havana]], Cuba) * ''[[Cabaret Red Light]]'' ([[Philadelphia]], USA) * ''[[VIVA Cabaret Showbar]]'' ([[Blackpool]], UK) * ''[[90 Degrees & Rising]]'' (Dunes Hotel & Casino, Las Vegas)<ref>{{cite news|title=Celebrating the Las Vegas showgirl: An icon lives on in one group’s evolving passion project|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2016/jun/13/celebrating-the-las-vegas-showgirl-an-icon-lives-o/|author=J.D. Morris|date=13 June 2016|newspaper=Las Vegas Sun}}</ref> {{div col end}}
== Showgirls in popular culture == * The ''Gold Diggers'' films, including ''[[The Gold Diggers (1923 film)|The Gold Diggers]]'' (silent, 1923), ''[[Gold Diggers of Broadway]]'' (1929), ''[[Gold Diggers of 1933]]'' (1933), ''[[Gold Diggers of 1935]]'' (1935), ''[[Gold Diggers of 1937]]'' (1936), and ''[[Gold Diggers in Paris]]'' (1938) * ''[[Bolero (1934 film)|Bolero]]'', a 1934 film in which [[American burlesque]] dancer [[Sally Rand]] played a carnival showgirl and performed a [[fan dance]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Striptease: The Untold History of the Girlie Show|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mn48DwAAQBAJ|first=Rachel|last=Shteir|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2004|isbn=9780195300765|page=153}}</ref> * [[The Golddiggers]], a troupe that performed on ''[[The Dean Martin Show]]'' beginning in 1968 * ''[[Showgirls]]'', a 1995 movie directed by [[Paul Verhoeven]] and starring [[Elizabeth Berkley]] * ''[[Guys and Dolls]]'', a 1950 Broadway production, depicts a Miss Adelaide as the main character's fiancée, a singer and showgirl in various musical numbers. * [[Kylie Minogue]] was inspired by different types of showgirls and named and styled her [[Showgirl: The Greatest Hits Tour]] and [[Showgirl: The Homecoming Tour]] concerts after them. Showgirl themes can be seen at many corners through Minogue's entire career. * Several showgirl cars are seen at the [[Dinoco]] booth during the animated film ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]''; former [[Motorama]] show car [[Flo (Cars)|Flo]] displays vanity licence plate SHOGRL as a "Motorama 1957 showgirl".
