{{BLP sources|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Tricia Brock | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | othername = | occupation = Film director, film producer, television director, television writer | yearsactive = | spouse = 1979–present | domesticpartner = | website = }}
'''Tricia Brock''' is American film/television director, film producer and television writer.
==Career== Brock began her career working in television commercials.<ref name="efilmcritic">[http://efilmcritic.com/feature.php?feature=1808 Unclogging the Bottleneck: Writer-Director Tricia Brock on ‘Killer Diller’] by Dan Lybarger - Efilmcritic.com</ref> She was then recruited to write two episodes of the television series, ''[[Twin Peaks]]''. She continued to write for other television series namely, ''[[Knots Landing]]'', ''[[Family Law (TV series)|Family Law]]'' and the television film ''Due East'', directed by [[Helen Shaver]].
In 2002, Brock shifted her focus to directing. Making her directorial debut with the short film, ''The Car Kid'' starring [[James Franco]] and [[Brad Renfro]]. A portion of the film was later re-edited into the full-length feature ''[[Killer Diller]]'' which was screened at the [[South by Southwest|South by Southwest Film Festival]] and the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] in 2004.<ref name="efilmcritic"/>
In 2005, she began directing for television, directing episodes of ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'', ''[[Veronica Mars]]'', ''[[Ugly Betty]]'', ''[[The L Word]]'', ''[[Gossip Girl]]'', ''[[Breaking Bad]]'', ''[[30 Rock]]'', ''[[Hellcats]]'', ''[[White Collar (TV series)|White Collar]]'', ''[[Smash (U.S. TV series)|Smash]]'', ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]'', ''[[Mr. Robot (TV series)|Mr. Robot]]'' and other series.
